## Choosing Your Archetype

### Understanding Archetype Roles

Every archetype fills certain roles naturally:

**If you want to stand on the frontline and trade blows**, consider Fighter or Paladin. Both can wear substantial armor and survive focused enemy attention, though they approach combat differently.

**If you want to strike from range with precision and mobility**, consider Ranger or Rogue. Both excel at positioning and exploiting advantages, using agility over raw durability.

**If you want to reshape combat through magical power**, consider Wizard, Cleric, or Bard. Each offers different magical traditions and different approaches to spellcasting.

**If you want to blend martial capability with magical support**, consider Paladin or Bard. Both combine weapon skill with spellcasting, creating hybrid characters who adapt to varied challenges.

### The Four Spellcasting Archetypes

Four archetypes can cast spells, each approaching magic differently:

**Wizard** channels arcane magic through pure study and technique. You have the broadest spell selection and strongest direct damage, modified through metamagic to create precise effects. Most wizards avoid armor entirely, relying on Mage Armor and tactical positioning for defense.

**Cleric** channels divine magic granted by faith and devotion. You excel at healing and support, can wear medium armor without crippling your magic, and gain specialized powers through your chosen domain. You balance frontline presence with magical support.

**Bard** channels magic through performance and artistry. Your spells focus on utility and social situations rather than raw damage. You wear light armor comfortably, use Bardic Inspiration to multiply ally effectiveness, and serve as the party's versatile problem-solver.

**Paladin** channels divine magic through sacred oaths and conviction. You're the only heavy armor spellcaster, combining frontline durability with healing and smiting magic. Your spell selection is more limited, but your martial prowess compensates.

### The Three Martial Archetypes

Three archetypes focus entirely on physical capability without magical shortcuts:

**Fighter** represents pure martial excellence. You begin with Professional combat skill—better than any other archetype's combat ability. Your combat techniques chain together into devastating combinations, and your starting edge (Weapon Focus or Tough) shapes whether you emphasize damage or defense. You wear medium armor and can use shields, creating a versatile tactical package.

**Ranger** combines combat capability with wilderness expertise. Your Professional survival skill makes you invaluable outside combat, while your favored terrain bonus creates situations where you outperform everyone. You wear light armor for mobility, typically fight at range, and gain Fast Movement or Precise Strike to enhance your skirmishing style.

**Rogue** begins with two Professional skills—the only archetype with this advantage. Professional Stealth and Finesse make you exceptionally dangerous when circumstances favor precision over direct confrontation. You don't get a starting edge (your extra Professional skill compensates), but you develop gambits through play—high-risk, high-reward techniques earned through successful heists rather than standard advancement.

### Starting Skill Analysis

**Professional (+1) Skills** represent your core competency. At this level, you succeed 91% of the time at standard difficulty (TN 8). This is reliable expertise—the thing you do well enough to build a career around.

**Novice (-1) Skills** represent supporting capabilities. You succeed about 41% of the time at standard difficulty. Not reliable enough to stake everything on, but useful when combined with good tactics or favorable circumstances.

**Untrained Skills** carry a -2 penalty, reducing success to about 25% at standard difficulty. You can still attempt these actions, but you're gambling rather than applying expertise.

Through advances (earned via XP), you advance skills upward. Most characters reach Professional in multiple areas by mid-campaign (Seasoned/Veteran ranks) and push toward Expert (+2) in their primary focus.

### Starting Edge Decisions

Some archetypes choose a starting edge:

**Fighter** chooses between Weapon Focus (additional damage with chosen weapon type) or Tough (additional Guard). Weapon Focus suits aggressive damage dealers; Tough suits defenders who protect others. Neither choice is wrong—pick based on the fighter you want to play.

**Ranger** chooses between Fast Movement (+1 zone of movement per turn) or Precise Strike (reroll one damage die per attack). Fast Movement enables hit-and-run skirmishing; Precise Strike creates consistent damage output. Again, both work—choose your preferred style.

These choices don't lock you into permanent builds. They simply provide a starting direction that shapes your first few sessions.

### Equipment and Armor Considerations

Your starting armor profoundly affects how you play:

**Heavy Armor** (Paladin only) grants DR 4 but imposes -2 to Grace-based actions and -3 to Sorcery. You can absorb tremendous damage but move less gracefully and cast spells less effectively. Paladins accept this tradeoff because their build emphasizes durability and limited spellcasting.

**Medium Armor** (Fighter, Cleric) grants DR 2 with -1 to Grace and -1 to Sorcery. This balanced option lets you survive focused attacks while maintaining reasonable agility and decent spellcasting. Most balanced builds use medium armor.

**Light Armor** (Ranger, Rogue, Bard) grants DR 1 with no penalties. You trade protection for freedom of movement and full spellcasting capability. Light armor suits mobile combatants and primary spellcasters who can't afford the Sorcery penalty.

**No Armor** (Wizard) grants DR 0 but provides +1 to Sorcery and +1 zone of movement. Wizards typically use Mage Armor cantrip (grants +2 Guard) to compensate, creating a lightly defended but highly mobile and magically effective character.

Your archetype determines starting armor, but you can change armor types during play. A fighter might upgrade to heavy armor, a wizard might acquire enchanted robes, a ranger might switch to medium armor when dungeon-crawling. Starting armor establishes your baseline, not your permanent state.

### Archetype and Calling Synergy

Certain callings pair naturally with certain archetypes:

**Fighters** often embody Champion (protective strength), Guardian (helping through defense), or Sentinel (vigilant security). The martial protector archetype attracts these psychological patterns.

**Rangers** often embody Seeker (finding themselves in wilderness), Scholar (studying nature), or Sentinel (watching for danger). The wilderness wanderer attracts introspective, observant callings.

**Paladins** often embody Advocate (righteous truth), Guardian (selfless service), or Champion (strong protection). The divine warrior attracts conviction-driven callings.

**Rogues** often embody Seeker (discovering identity through adventure), Enthusiast (experiencing life), or Scholar (clever problem-solving). The cunning opportunist attracts curious, exploratory callings.

**Wizards** often embody Scholar (mastering knowledge), Seeker (understanding mysteries), or Advocate (pursuing truth). The arcane student attracts intellectual callings.

**Clerics** often embody Guardian (caring for others), Mediator (bringing peace), or Advocate (serving justice). The divine healer attracts nurturing, harmony-seeking callings.

**Bards** often embody Enthusiast (celebrating life), Mediator (connecting people), or Seeker (exploring experience). The performer attracts socially engaged, expressive callings.

But these are patterns, not rules. Against-type combinations create interesting character concepts:

- Advocate Rogue: A vigilante pursuing justice through unconventional means
- Champion Wizard: A competitive duel-focused mage who sees magic as strength
- Mediator Fighter: An enforcer who prevents violence through implied force
- Scholar Bard: A traveling academic who shares knowledge through performance

The system supports whatever concept you want to explore.

