## Playing Your Archetype

### Understanding Your Unique Subsystem

Every archetype has a special mechanical framework:

**Combat Techniques (Fighter)** - You learn individual techniques by spending advances (earned through XP) and chain them together during fights. A technique might let you disarm an enemy, follow up with a precise strike, then intimidate nearby foes. The system rewards tactical thinking and creates combat depth beyond "I attack again."

**Favored Terrain (Ranger)** - You choose terrain types (urban, forest, mountain, etc.) and gain significant bonuses when operating in those environments. These aren't minor flavor bonuses—they're substantial mechanical advantages that make you exceptional in your element. Expand your terrain types by spending advances.

**Divine Oath (Paladin)** - Work with your GM to define your oath's restrictions and powers. Your oath might grant bonus damage against oath-breakers, protective auras for allies, or smiting capabilities against specific enemy types. Oath violations have consequences but shouldn't destroy your character—work with your GM to handle lapses and redemption.

**Gambits (Rogue)** - You don't learn gambits through standard advancement. Instead, you unlock them through successful heists and clever plans. Pull off an elaborate infiltration, and your GM might award a new gambit representing that technique. Gambits are high-risk, high-reward—spectacular successes when they work, dramatic failures when they don't.

**Metamagic (Wizard)** - You learn techniques that modify your spells. Heighten a spell to increase damage, quicken it to cast faster, widen it to affect more area. Each metamagic option costs additional Momentum, creating resource decisions. Start with 1-2 options, gain more by spending advances.

**Divine Domain (Cleric)** - Your deity grants specialized powers based on their domain (War, Knowledge, Life, Nature, etc.). Domain powers supplement your spells—a War domain cleric gains combat bonuses, a Knowledge domain cleric gains information-gathering capabilities. Domains expand as you gain advances.

**Bardic Inspiration (Bard)** - You grant allies bonus dice to add to their rolls. Start with d4s, upgrade to larger dice (d6, d8, d10, d12) as you advance through ranks. Your pool of inspiration dice grows with advancement. You multiply ally effectiveness rather than directly solving problems yourself.

### Tactical Considerations by Archetype

**Fighter** - Position yourself between enemies and squishier allies. Use your high Guard and armor to absorb attacks. Chain combat techniques to create cascading effects. Switch stances based on whether you're pushing forward (Aggressive) or holding ground (Defensive).

**Ranger** - Maintain distance from enemies. Use your mobility to create favorable positions. Fight in your favored terrain whenever possible—the bonuses are significant. Switch to melee if cornered, but your strength is avoiding that situation.

**Paladin** - Stand on the frontline and dare enemies to ignore you. Your heavy armor lets you survive focused fire. Use healing spells on allies in danger. Your smiting capabilities make you dangerous to specific enemy types—learn what your oath makes you good at killing.

**Rogue** - Avoid fair fights. Use stealth to create advantages. Position for flanking bonuses. Save gambits for moments when spectacular success changes everything. Your high skills make you valuable outside combat—take the lead in social and exploration challenges.

**Wizard** - Build Momentum with cantrips early in fights, then unleash powerful spells. Stay away from enemies—your low HP and armor make you fragile. Use metamagic to modify spells for specific situations. Your versatility is your strength; choose spells that cover different problem types.

**Cleric** - Balance healing allies with supporting through domain powers. Your medium armor lets you operate at medium range safely. Don't burn all your resources healing—sometimes dealing damage or controlling enemies prevents more damage than healing fixes.

**Bard** - Support allies with inspiration before combat gets serious. Use utility spells to create advantages. Your light armor and low HP make direct combat dangerous, but your social skills and magical versatility make you invaluable in varied situations.

