## Game Master Guidance

### Balancing Party Composition

The ideal party has coverage:
- Someone who can take hits (Fighter, Paladin)
- Someone who deals consistent damage (any archetype can do this with right build)
- Someone who can heal or prevent damage (Cleric, Paladin, Bard)
- Someone who handles utility and problems (Rogue, Bard, Wizard, Ranger)

But any composition works if players understand their roles and work together. Four fighters can succeed through tactics and coordination. Four wizards can succeed through overwhelming magical versatility.

Don't force players to choose archetypes for party balance. Encourage them to play what interests them, then adjust encounters to their composition.

### Supporting Unique Subsystems

**Combat Techniques (Fighter)** - Award new techniques as treasure or training rewards. Let players discover combinations through experimentation. When a fighter chains three techniques into a devastating combo, make it feel impactful.

**Favored Terrain (Ranger)** - Make terrain matter. Don't just describe the forest, create mechanical situations where forest knowledge provides advantages. Rangers should feel exceptional in their terrain, not merely slightly better.

**Divine Oath (Paladin)** - Work with the player to define oath tenets. Violating the oath should have consequences (temporary loss of powers, need for atonement) but shouldn't end the character. Redemption arcs are dramatic and engaging.

**Gambits (Rogue)** - Reward clever heist planning with new gambit options. Gambits should feel risky—high reward when they succeed, dramatic failure when they don't. Don't make every gambit succeed; the risk is part of the appeal.

**Metamagic (Wizard)** - Let wizards feel like masters of magic. Metamagic should enable tricks other casters can't pull off. The Momentum cost creates meaningful decisions about when to use standard spells versus enhanced versions.

**Divine Domain (Cleric)** - Make domains feel distinct. A War cleric should feel different from a Knowledge cleric both mechanically and narratively. Domain powers should be significant enough to matter without overshadowing spellcasting.

**Bardic Inspiration (Bard)** - Let inspiration dice turn failures into successes. When a bard gives inspiration and it changes the outcome, highlight that moment. Bards should feel like they make everyone better.

### Starting Equipment Customization

Players sometimes want to modify starting equipment:

**Weapon Swaps** - Allow swaps within the same category. A fighter starting with a longsword can swap for a mace or battleaxe. Don't allow radical changes (longsword to bow) without narrative justification.

**Armor Downgrades** - Players can choose lighter armor and keep the cost difference in coins. A fighter might start with light armor instead of medium, gaining coins for other purchases.

**Gear Substitutions** - Allow equivalent-value gear swaps. If starting gear includes rope and pitons, a player might swap for a grappling hook and oil.

General principle: Maintain the archetype's intended capability while allowing reasonable personalization.

### Common Questions

**Can characters multiclass?**
No. Autumn Phoenix RPG doesn't use multiclassing. Instead, use specialties and advance options to add capabilities from other archetypes. A fighter who wants magical ability can learn basic spellcasting at higher ranks (Heroic+) if their attributes support it.

**Can characters retrain or change archetypes?**
Rarely, with strong narrative justification. A wizard who abandons magic to become a fighter would need significant story development. Work with players who want radical changes, but treat it as a major character arc, not a casual respec.

**Why does Rogue start with two Professional skills but no edge?**
Balance. Two Professional skills is roughly equivalent in power to one Professional skill plus a starting edge. Rogues trade the immediate capability of an edge for broader skill competency.

**Can non-spellcasters learn magic later?**
Yes, if they meet attribute requirements. A fighter with high Mind could learn some spells at higher ranks (Heroic+). They won't cast as effectively as Wizard (no Professional Sorcery), but basic magic is accessible to anyone who studies and has the mental capability.

